> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PEECT414 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING
> - **Module:** Module 3
> - **Topic:** Reading Console Input

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**Console Input** refers to the process of accepting data from the standard input stream (typically the keyboard) into a running Java program at runtime. In the Java Standard Edition (Java SE) platform, console input is facilitated by classes residing in two primary packages: `java.util` (which provides the high-level `Scanner` class) and `java.io` (which provides the legacy stream-based classes such as `BufferedReader`, `InputStreamReader`, and `Console`).

> [!NOTE]
> **Standard Input Stream (`System.in`):** In Java, the static field `System.in` is an instance of `java.io.InputStream` that is automatically connected to the keyboard (or the active console) when the program begins execution. All console input techniques ultimately read bytes from this stream.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Module 3 Focus:** The syllabus specifically emphasizes the `Scanner` class as the primary mechanism for reading input, along with `BufferedReader` for performance-oriented and tokenized input operations.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Restaurant Order System

Imagine a restaurant scenario to understand the three layers of console input in Java:

| Layer | Restaurant Analogy | Java Equivalent |
|---|---|---|
| **Customer (User)** | Speaks the order aloud | Keyboard (physical input) |
| **Waiter (Translator)** | Converts spoken words into structured form | `InputStreamReader` (byte → char) |
| **Head Chef (Processor)** | Parses the order into specific ingredients | `Scanner` or `BufferedReader` (parse tokens) |

When a customer places an order, the raw spoken words (bytes) need a waiter (InputStreamReader) to translate them into a written format (characters), which is then handed to the head chef (`Scanner`/`BufferedReader`) who parses them into actual ingredients (typed data — `int`, `double`, `String`).

### 1.3 The Three Primary Approaches

Java provides **three** standard ways to read console input:

1. **`Scanner` class** (Recommended for beginners and most academic contexts) — Simplest, most readable, has built-in parsing methods.
2. **`BufferedReader` + `InputStreamReader`** (Recommended for competitive programming and performance) — Faster, supports string-based tokenization.
3. **`Console` class** (Recommended for secure password input) — Provides methods for secure password reading where input is masked.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The `Scanner` Class — Operational Breakdown

The `Scanner` class (introduced in Java 5.0, residing in `java.util`) breaks its input into **tokens** using a delimiter pattern. By default, the delimiter is **whitespace** (spaces, tabs, newlines).

**Constructor Signatures (High-Yield for KTU):**

```
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);       // Reads from keyboard
Scanner sc = new Scanner(File);            // Reads from file
Scanner sc = new Scanner(String);          // Reads from a String
```

**Core Methods — The "Why" and "How":**

- `nextInt()` → Reads the next token as a `primitive int`. **Why?** Pre-validates the input; throws `InputMismatchException` if non-integer.
- `nextDouble()` → Reads the next token as a `primitive double`. **Why?** Locale-sensitive decimal parsing.
- `nextLine()` → Reads the rest of the current line as a `String` (including spaces). **Why?** Used for full-line input.
- `next()` → Reads the next token (up to whitespace) as a `String`. **Why?** Token-by-token string reading.
- `nextBoolean()`, `nextLong()`, `nextFloat()`, `nextByte()`, `nextShort()` → Type-specific readers.
- `hasNextInt()`, `hasNextDouble()` → **Predictive** methods that return `true` if the next token can be parsed as the specified type. **Why?** Prevents runtime crashes on invalid input.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The `nextLine()` Trap (Most Common KTU Pitfall):** After calling `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, or `next()`, the newline character (`\n`) is **left behind** in the input buffer. The immediate next call to `nextLine()` will return an **empty string**. The fix is to consume the leftover newline with an extra `sc.nextLine()` call.

### 2.2 The `BufferedReader` Class — Operational Breakdown

`BufferedReader` is a **character-stream** class in `java.io` that reads text from a character-input stream, buffering characters to provide efficient reading of characters, arrays, and lines.

**Operational Chain (Why Two Classes Are Needed):**

```
System.in (byte stream)
      ↓
InputStreamReader (byte → char converter, bridges byte and char streams)
      ↓
BufferedReader (adds buffering for performance, adds readLine())
```

**Key Method:**

- `String readLine()` → Reads a line of text, terminated by `\n`, `\r`, or `\r\n`. Returns `null` at end of stream. **Throws** `IOException` — hence mandatory `throws` declaration or `try-catch`.

### 2.3 The `Console` Class — Operational Breakdown

Introduced in Java 6, `Console` is obtained via `System.console()`. It is the **only** standard class that allows reading a password without echoing the characters to the screen.

- `String readLine()` → Reads a single line of text.
- `char[] readPassword()` → Reads password (input is not displayed). **Why `char[]` and not `String`?** Strings are immutable and remain in the string pool until garbage-collected — a security risk. `char[]` arrays can be explicitly zeroed out.

### 2.4 KTU Formula / Method Cheat Sheet

| Method | Class | Return Type | Reads | Throws Exception | Buffer Issue? |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `nextInt()` | `Scanner` | `int` | Token (int) | `InputMismatchException` | Leaves `\n` |
| `nextDouble()` | `Scanner` | `double` | Token (double) | `InputMismatchException` | Leaves `\n` |
| `nextLine()` | `Scanner` | `String` | Full line | `NoSuchElementException` | None |
| `next()` | `Scanner` | `String` | Single token | `NoSuchElementException` | Leaves `\n` |
| `hasNextInt()` | `Scanner` | `boolean` | Peeks next token | None | None |
| `readLine()` | `BufferedReader` | `String` | Full line | `IOException` | None |
| `readPassword()` | `Console` | `char[]` | Full line (masked) | `IOError` | None |

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

Console input mechanisms are foundational in:
- **CLI tools** (e.g., Git, Docker CLI)
- **Interactive form-based desktop apps**
- **Automated testing scripts** that read test data from stdin
- **Embedded systems** that receive configuration from a serial terminal
- **Cybersecurity tools** that require secure password entry (using `Console.readPassword()`)

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Code Analysis & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Example 1 — Reading Multiple Data Types with `Scanner`

**Problem:** Write a Java program to read a student's name (String), roll number (int), and CGPA (double) from the console and display them.

**Code:**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class StudentDetails {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Create Scanner object bound to System.in
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Step 2: Prompt and read String (full line including spaces)
        System.out.print("Enter name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();

        // Step 3: Prompt and read int
        System.out.print("Enter roll number: ");
        int roll = sc.nextInt();

        // Step 4: Prompt and read double
        System.out.print("Enter CGPA: ");
        double cgpa = sc.nextDouble();

        // Step 5: Display
        System.out.println("\n--- Student Details ---");
        System.out.println("Name   : " + name);
        System.out.println("Roll No: " + roll);
        System.out.println("CGPA   : " + cgpa);

        // Step 6: Close the Scanner
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Sample Run (Input Trace):**

```
Enter name: Ananya Krishnan
Enter roll number: 47
Enter CGPA: 9.12

--- Student Details ---
Name   : Ananya Krishnan
Roll No: 47
CGPA   : 9.12
```

**Step-by-Step Logic:**

1. **`new Scanner(System.in)`** — Allocates a Scanner that reads from the standard input stream. Internally, Scanner uses a `Readable` interface and a `Pattern` (regex) to tokenize input.
2. **`sc.nextLine()`** — Reads characters until it encounters `\n` (or `\r\n`). The newline is consumed but not returned.
3. **`sc.nextInt()`** — Scans the next token, validates it against the regex `[-+]?[0-9]+`, parses to `int`, and returns. The trailing `\n` is left in the buffer.
4. **`sc.nextDouble()`** — Scans the next token, validates against the floating-point regex, parses to `double`.
5. **`sc.close()`** — Releases the underlying resource. Good practice; also prevents `ResourceLeakWarning` in IDEs.

### 3.2 Example 2 — Demonstrating the `nextLine()` Buffer Trap

**Problem:** Demonstrate and resolve the classic Scanner buffer-leftover problem.

**Buggy Code (Loses the "Address" Input):**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
public class BufferTrap {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter roll: ");
        int roll = sc.nextInt();   // reads "47", leaves "\n" in buffer

        System.out.print("Enter name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine(); // reads "" (empty) — consumes the leftover "\n"

        System.out.print("Enter address: ");
        String addr = sc.nextLine(); // reads "Kochi Kerala"

        System.out.println("Roll: " + roll);
        System.out.println("Name: '" + name + "'");  // prints empty!
        System.out.println("Address: " + addr);
    }
}
```

**Fixed Code (Consumes Leftover Newline):**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
public class BufferFixed {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter roll: ");
        int roll = sc.nextInt();
        sc.nextLine();  // <-- THE FIX: consume the leftover newline

        System.out.print("Enter name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.print("Enter address: ");
        String addr = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.println("Roll: " + roll);
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Address: " + addr);
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Explanation of the Fix:**

After `nextInt()` consumes `47`, the stream pointer sits just before `\n`. The `sc.nextLine()` call (the dummy call) consumes that `\n` so the **next** `nextLine()` call begins reading from the actual user input.

### 3.3 Example 3 — `BufferedReader` with `InputStreamReader`

**Problem:** Read two integers separated by space using BufferedReader.

**Code:**

```java
import java.io.*;

public class BufferedReaderDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Step 1: Create the bridge from byte stream to char stream
        InputStreamReader isr = new InputStreamReader(System.in);

        // Step 2: Wrap in BufferedReader for efficient line-based reading
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(isr);

        System.out.print("Enter two integers: ");
        String line = br.readLine();       // reads "45 78"

        // Step 3: Tokenize using String.split()
        String[] tokens = line.split(" ");

        // Step 4: Parse each token
        int a = Integer.parseInt(tokens[0]);
        int b = Integer.parseInt(tokens[1]);

        System.out.println("Sum = " + (a + b));

        // Step 5: Close the stream
        br.close();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Logic:**

1. **`InputStreamReader isr = new InputStreamReader(System.in);`** — Converts the byte stream from `System.in` into a character stream using the default charset (usually UTF-8).
2. **`BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(isr);`** — Adds an internal buffer (default size: **8192 characters**) for efficient reading. Each `readLine()` call is O(1) amortized.
3. **`br.readLine()`** — Returns the line as a `String`; **does not** include the line terminator. Returns `null` on EOF.
4. **`line.split(" ")`** — Splits the string by space into a `String[]`.
5. **`Integer.parseInt()`** — Static utility that converts a `String` representation to a primitive `int`. Throws `NumberFormatException` if the string is not a valid integer.
6. **`throws IOException`** — `readLine()` declares this checked exception, so the caller **must** handle or declare it.

### 3.4 Example 4 — Secure Password Reading with `Console`

**Problem:** Read a username and a masked password from the console.

**Code:**

```java
public class SecureLogin {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Console console = System.console();

        if (console == null) {
            System.out.println("No console available. Run from terminal.");
            return;
        }

        String username = console.readLine("Enter username: ");
        char[] password = console.readPassword("Enter password: ");

        // Simulated check
        if (username.equals("admin") && new String(password).equals("secret123")) {
            System.out.println("Login successful!");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid credentials.");
        }

        // Best practice: zero out the password array
        java.util.Arrays.fill(password, ' ');
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Logic:**

1. **`System.console()`** — Returns the unique `Console` object associated with the current JVM. Returns `null` if invoked from an IDE (e.g., Eclipse, IntelliJ) that does not allocate a real console.
2. **`console.readLine(prompt)`** — Displays the prompt and reads a line of text.
3. **`console.readPassword(prompt)`** — Displays the prompt; the user's keystrokes are **not echoed** to the terminal. Returns a `char[]` (not `String`).
4. **`Arrays.fill(password, ' ')`** — Overwrites the password array with spaces, mitigating memory-dump attacks.

### 3.5 Comprehensive Method Flow — `hasNextInt()` Validation Pattern

**Problem:** Keep prompting the user until a valid integer is entered.

**Code:**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class RobustInput {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int number = 0;
        boolean valid = false;

        while (!valid) {
            System.out.print("Enter a positive integer: ");
            if (sc.hasNextInt()) {
                number = sc.nextInt();
                if (number > 0) {
                    valid = true;
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Must be positive. Try again.");
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("Invalid input. Try again.");
                sc.next(); // discard the invalid token
            }
        }

        System.out.println("You entered: " + number);
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Logic Trace:**

- `hasNextInt()` performs a **non-destructive** lookahead. It checks the next token's type without consuming it.
- If invalid, `sc.next()` is called to discard the bad token (else the loop becomes infinite).
- The `valid` flag exits the loop only on a positive integer.

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 Input Flow Architecture — From Keyboard to Variable

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User types on keyboard]:::input --> B[OS captures keystrokes as bytes]
    B --> C[System.in InputStream]
    C --> D{Input Method Chosen}
    D -->|Scanner| E1[Scanner class]
    D -->|BufferedReader| E2[InputStreamReader bridge]
    E2 --> F[BufferedReader wrapper]
    D -->|Console| E3[System.console]
    E1 --> G1[Tokenization by whitespace]
    F --> G2[Line-based readLine]
    E3 --> G3[Line / Masked read]
    G1 --> H1[nextInt, nextDouble, nextLine etc.]
    G2 --> H2[String split and parse]
    G3 --> H3[Variable assignment]
    H1 --> I[Java primitive or String variable]
    H2 --> I
    H3 --> I
    I:::output --> J[Program logic uses input]

    classDef input fill:#cce5ff,stroke:#0050b3,color:#000
    classDef output fill:#d4edda,stroke:#155724,color:#000
```

**Reading the Diagram:**
- The flow begins with raw keyboard bytes (Step A → B).
- All three Java input mechanisms ultimately consume from `System.in` (Step C).
- Each path applies its own parsing strategy before producing a typed variable (Step I) usable by program logic (Step J).

### 4.2 Class Hierarchy of Input Mechanisms

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[java.lang.System] -->|static field| B[System.in : InputStream]
    A -->|static method| C[System.console : Console]
    B --> D[InputStreamReader]
    D --> E[BufferedReader]
    B --> F[Scanner]
    C --> G[Console]
    E --> H[String readLine]
    F --> I[nextInt, nextDouble, nextLine]
    G --> J[readLine, readPassword]

    classDef sysClass fill:#fff3cd,stroke:#856404,color:#000
    classDef ioClass fill:#f8d7da,stroke:#721c24,color:#000
    classDef utilClass fill:#d1ecf1,stroke:#0c5460,color:#000

    class A,B,C sysClass
    class D,E,G,H ioClass
    class F,I,J utilClass
```

**Reading the Diagram:**
- `System.in` (a byte `InputStream`) is the **universal source**.
- `InputStreamReader` is the **bridge** that converts bytes to characters — required because `BufferedReader` is a character-stream class.
- `Scanner` directly wraps `System.in` without needing the bridge because it handles bytes internally.

### 4.3 The `nextLine()` Buffer Trap — Visual Trace

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User Keyboard
    participant B as Input Buffer
    participant P as Java Program
    Note over B: Initial state: empty
    U->>B: types "47" + Enter
    Note over B: [4][7][\n]
    P->>B: sc.nextInt()
    B-->>P: returns 47
    Note over B: [\n]  ← LEFTOVER!
    P->>B: sc.nextLine()
    B-->>P: returns ""  ← BUG!
    Note over B: empty
    P->>B: sc.nextLine() (real input)
    U->>B: types "Kochi" + Enter
    B-->>P: returns "Kochi"
```

**Reading the Sequence:**
- The newline character `[\n]` remains in the buffer after `nextInt()`.
- The very next `nextLine()` consumes only this newline, returning an empty string.
- The "Kochi" input is therefore assigned to the *second* `nextLine()` call, not the first.

<!-- SECTION_4_END -->

<!-- SECTION_5_START -->
## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024 Model]**
*Explain any three methods of the `Scanner` class used to read input from the console, with one example each.*

**Model Answer (3 marks — 1 mark per method):**

The `Scanner` class in `java.util` provides type-specific methods to parse console input.

1. **`int nextInt()`** — Reads the next token and parses it as a primitive `int`.
   Example: `int age = sc.nextInt();`
2. **`double nextDouble()`** — Reads the next token and parses it as a primitive `double`.
   Example: `double salary = sc.nextDouble();`
3. **`String nextLine()`** — Reads the remainder of the current line (including spaces) as a `String`.
   Example: `String name = sc.nextLine();`

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023 Model]**
*Differentiate between `Scanner` and `BufferedReader` for reading console input in Java. (Any three points)*

**Model Answer (3 marks — 1 mark per point):**

| Aspect | `Scanner` | `BufferedReader` |
|---|---|---|
| **Package** | `java.util` | `java.io` |
| **Parsing** | Built-in parsing methods (`nextInt`, etc.) | No parsing; returns `String`; manual `parseInt` needed |
| **Thread Safety** | Not thread-safe | Thread-safe (all methods are `synchronized`) |
| **Performance** | Slower (uses regex internally) | Faster (uses character buffer) |
| **Exception** | Unchecked `InputMismatchException` | Checked `IOException` |

---

### Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

> **Internal Choice Rule (KTU 2024 ESE Pattern):** Answer **either** Question A **or** Question B in full.

---

### ✦ Question A (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — June 2024 Model]

**(a)** Explain the `Scanner` class in Java. Discuss its commonly used methods with examples. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program that reads a student's name, register number, and three subject marks from the console, calculates the total and average, and displays the result using formatted output. Handle the `InputMismatchException` appropriately. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Solution to Q.A (a) — 7 Marks

**Definition (2 marks):** The `Scanner` class, defined in the `java.util` package, is used to read input from various sources including the keyboard, files, and strings. It uses a delimiter pattern (default: whitespace) to break the input into tokens and provides built-in methods to parse tokens into primitive types and strings.

**Construction (1 mark):**
```java
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
```

**Commonly Used Methods (4 marks — 0.5 each example):**

| Method | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `nextInt()` | Reads an `int` | `int x = sc.nextInt();` |
| `nextDouble()` | Reads a `double` | `double d = sc.nextDouble();` |
| `nextLine()` | Reads a line (with spaces) | `String s = sc.nextLine();` |
| `next()` | Reads a single token (no spaces) | `String t = sc.next();` |
| `nextBoolean()` | Reads a `boolean` | `boolean b = sc.nextBoolean();` |
| `hasNextInt()` | Checks if next token is `int` | `if (sc.hasNextInt()) { ... }` |
| `nextLong()`, `nextFloat()` | Reads `long`, `float` | `long l = sc.nextLong();` |
| `close()` | Closes the scanner | `sc.close();` |

---

#### Solution to Q.A (b) — 7 Marks

**Complete Java Program:**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
import java.util.InputMismatchException;

public class StudentResult {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        try {
            System.out.print("Enter name: ");
            String name = sc.nextLine();

            System.out.print("Enter register number: ");
            long regNo = sc.nextLong();

            System.out.print("Enter mark 1: ");
            double m1 = sc.nextDouble();
            System.out.print("Enter mark 2: ");
            double m2 = sc.nextDouble();
            System.out.print("Enter mark 3: ");
            double m3 = sc.nextDouble();

            double total = m1 + m2 + m3;
            double avg = total / 3.0;

            System.out.printf("%n--- Result ---%n");
            System.out.printf("Name       : %s%n", name);
            System.out.printf("Register No: %d%n", regNo);
            System.out.printf("Total      : %.2f%n", total);
            System.out.printf("Average    : %.2f%n", avg);
        } catch (InputMismatchException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: Invalid input type entered.");
        } finally {
            sc.close();
        }
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Explanation:**

1. **Imports (0.5 mark):** `Scanner` for input; `InputMismatchException` for error handling.
2. **Reading inputs (2 marks):** Sequential reads — `nextLine()` for name (with spaces), `nextLong()` for register number, three `nextDouble()` calls for marks.
3. **Calculation (1 mark):** `total = m1 + m2 + m3`; `avg = total / 3.0` (note the `3.0` to avoid integer division).
4. **Formatted output (1.5 marks):** `System.out.printf()` with format specifiers `%s`, `%d`, `%.2f`.
5. **Exception handling (1.5 marks):** `try-catch-finally` block. `InputMismatchException` is caught when non-numeric data is entered for numeric fields. `finally` guarantees Scanner closure.
6. **Compilation/output (0.5 mark):** Correctly compiles under `javac` and runs under `java`.

---

### ✦ Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — Dec 2024 Model]

**(a)** Explain the `BufferedReader` class and the role of `InputStreamReader` in reading console input. Write a Java program to read a line of integers separated by spaces and compute their sum. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Discuss the `nextLine()` buffer problem in the `Scanner` class. Write a Java program demonstrating the issue and its solution. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Solution to Q.B (a) — 7 Marks

**Conceptual Explanation (3 marks):**

- **`InputStreamReader`:** A bridge class in `java.io` that converts a byte stream (`InputStream`) into a character stream (`Reader`). It uses a default or specified character encoding (e.g., UTF-8).
- **`BufferedReader`:** Wraps a `Reader` to provide buffering (default buffer size: 8192 chars) and the convenient `readLine()` method that returns a `String` representation of one line. It throws `IOException`, a checked exception.
- **Why both?** `System.in` is a byte stream; `BufferedReader` requires a character stream. `InputStreamReader` is the mandatory intermediary.

**Program (4 marks):**

```java
import java.io.*;

public class SumOfIntegers {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        System.out.print("Enter integers separated by spaces: ");
        String line = br.readLine();

        String[] tokens = line.trim().split("\\s+");
        int sum = 0;
        for (String token : tokens) {
            sum += Integer.parseInt(token);
        }

        System.out.println("Sum = " + sum);
        br.close();
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

- `line.trim().split("\\s+")` — Trims leading/trailing whitespace, then splits by one or more whitespace characters (`\\s+` is the regex for whitespace).
- `Integer.parseInt()` — Converts each token to `int`. Throws `NumberFormatException` for non-integer tokens.
- `throws IOException` — Declares the checked exception from `readLine()`.
- `br.close()` — Releases the underlying resource.

---

#### Solution to Q.B (b) — 7 Marks

**Explanation of the Buffer Problem (3 marks):**

The `Scanner` class uses an internal buffer. Methods like `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, and `next()` read only the numeric/string token but **leave the trailing newline character (`\n`) in the buffer**. The next call to `nextLine()` reads up to that newline and returns an **empty string**. This is a frequent source of bugs in Java programs.

**Program Demonstrating Bug (2 marks):**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
public class BufferBug {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter age: ");
        int age = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter city: ");
        String city = sc.nextLine();  // BUG: returns "" — skips user input

        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("City: " + city);
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Program with Solution (2 marks):**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
public class BufferFixed {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter age: ");
        int age = sc.nextInt();
        sc.nextLine();  // SOLUTION: consume leftover newline

        System.out.print("Enter city: ");
        String city = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("City: " + city);
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Solution Recap:** Inserting a `sc.nextLine()` call immediately after `nextInt()`/`nextDouble()`/`next()` consumes the leftover newline character, allowing the subsequent `nextLine()` to read the actual user input.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting to import** `java.util.Scanner` or `java.io.*` (loses 0.5–1 mark).
> 2. **Not handling `IOException`** for `BufferedReader.readLine()` — without `throws` or `try-catch`, the code **will not compile** (loses 1–2 marks).
> 3. **Using `==` instead of `.equals()`** for String comparison in console input programs (loses 1 mark — common KTU deduction).
> 4. **Ignoring the `nextLine()` buffer trap** in multi-step input programs — examiner specifically tests this (loses 1–2 marks).
> 5. **Integer division in average calculation** — writing `total / 3` instead of `total / 3.0` produces wrong output for non-divisible totals (loses 1 mark).
> 6. **Not closing the Scanner** — minor deduction (0.5 mark) in strict valuation.

---

### 📌 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Console input in Java** is read from `System.in`, a byte `InputStream` connected to the keyboard.
- **`Scanner`** (in `java.util`) is the **most commonly used** input class; offers type-specific methods (`nextInt`, `nextDouble`, `nextLine`, `next`, etc.).
- **`BufferedReader`** (in `java.io`) requires `InputStreamReader` as a bridge; offers `readLine()` returning a `String`; throws checked `IOException`.
- **`Console`** (obtained via `System.console()`) is used for **secure password input** with `readPassword()` returning a `char[]`.
- **`hasNextInt()` / `hasNextDouble()`** are non-destructive validation methods that prevent `InputMismatchException`.
- **The `nextLine()` buffer trap:** Always call an extra `sc.nextLine()` after `nextInt()`/`nextDouble()`/`next()` to consume the leftover newline.
- **Tokenizer:** `Scanner` uses whitespace by default; `BufferedReader.readLine()` + `String.split()` is the manual tokenization approach.
- **Performance:** `BufferedReader` is **faster** than `Scanner` for large input volumes (relevant for competitive programming and KTU lab viva questions).
- **Resource management:** Always call `sc.close()` or `br.close()` to release system resources; use `try-with-resources` in modern Java code.
- **String comparison:** Use `.equals()` not `==` when comparing input strings — the most common KTU valuation deduction.
- **Locale-sensitive decimals:** `nextDouble()` uses the **default locale**; in some locales the decimal separator is `,` (comma) not `.` (period). For locale-independent parsing, use `Scanner.useLocale(Locale.US)`.
