# 📘 Module 4: Model View Controller (MVC)

## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Definition — Model-View-Controller (MVC):**
> *MVC is a **software architectural design pattern** that decomposes an interactive application into **three loosely-coupled, cooperating components** — the **Model** (data + business logic), the **View** (presentation/UI), and the **Controller** (input/event handler) — to achieve **separation of concerns**, **modularity**, and **independent maintainability**.*

The pattern was originally formulated by **Trygve Reenskaug** at Xerox PARC in **1979** for the Smalltalk environment, and is today the *de-facto* foundation of virtually every modern UI framework (Java Swing, Spring MVC, .NET MVC, Ruby on Rails, Django, Angular, Flutter, etc.).

### 1.2 The Three Pillars of MVC

| Pillar | Responsibility | Knows About |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Model** | Holds data, enforces business rules, notifies observers on change. | **Itself only.** Never about View or Controller. |
| **View** | Renders the Model's data into a user-visible form. | **Model** (read-only). Does not know the Controller exists. |
| **Controller** | Translates user input/events into Model updates and View selections. | **Both Model and View**, and is the only conduit between them. |

### 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — "The Restaurant"

> [!NOTE]
> Imagine MVC as a **three-tier restaurant**:
> - The **Customer** sees only the **menu and the dish served** → that is the **View**.
> - The **Waiter** takes the order, calls it to the kitchen, and brings back the dish → that is the **Controller**.
> - The **Kitchen** stores ingredients, follows recipes (business rules), and prepares the dish → that is the **Model**.
>
> The customer never enters the kitchen, the kitchen never sees the customer, and the waiter orchestrates the exchange. If you redesign the menu (View), the kitchen (Model) keeps working unchanged. If you change the recipe (Model), the menu's wording may need an update, but the waiter protocol is the same.

### 1.4 Why MVC Matters in KTU Examinations

> [!TIP]
> KTU examiners reward answers that explicitly mention: **separation of concerns**, **loose coupling**, **high cohesion**, **reusability**, **multiple synchronized views**, and **ease of maintenance**. Memorising these seven adjectives can convert a 6-mark answer into a 14-mark answer.

