# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> Because MVC is an **architectural pattern** rather than a closed-form equation, the "derivation" below is the **exhaustive build-up of a working Java MVC program**, written exactly as a KTU 14-mark answer expects.

## 3.1 Problem Statement

> Design a Java application using the **MVC pattern** that maintains a single `Student` record (name, roll number, marks), allows the user to **edit** and **view** it through a Swing-based GUI, and demonstrates **clear separation** of Model, View, and Controller.

## 3.2 Architecture Snapshot (textual)

```
User ⇄ View ⇄ Controller ⇄ Model
                          ⇡
                       notifies
                          ⇟
                        View
```

## 3.3 Step 1 — The MODEL (Pure Java, zero UI imports)

```java
// File: StudentModel.java  — PURE MODEL, no javax.swing imports.
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class StudentModel {
    // --- 1. State (data) ---
    private String name;
    private int    rollNo;
    private double marks;

    // --- 2. Observers (any View can subscribe) ---
    private final List<Runnable> listeners = new ArrayList<>();

    // --- 3. Constructor ---
    public StudentModel(String name, int rollNo, double marks) {
        this.name   = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        this.marks  = marks;
    }

    // --- 4. Getters (read-only public surface) ---
    public String getName()   { return name; }
    public int    getRollNo() { return rollNo; }
    public double getMarks()  { return marks; }

    // --- 5. Business rule (computed property) ---
    public String getGrade() {
        if (marks >= 90) return "A+";
        if (marks >= 80) return "A";
        if (marks >= 70) return "B+";
        if (marks >= 60) return "B";
        if (marks >= 50) return "C";
        return "F";
    }

    // --- 6. Mutators (only Controller should call these) ---
    public void setName(String name) {
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name cannot be empty.");
        }
        this.name = name;
        fireChange();
    }

    public void setMarks(double marks) {
        if (marks < 0 || marks > 100) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Marks must be in 0..100.");
        }
        this.marks = marks;
        fireChange();
    }

    // --- 7. Observer plumbing ---
    public void addChangeListener(Runnable r) { listeners.add(r); }
    private void fireChange() {
        for (Runnable r : listeners) r.run();
    }
}
```

**Step 1 explanation (line by line):**
- Lines **1–2**: We deliberately **do not import `javax.swing.*`** — that is the litmus test for a clean Model.
- Lines **5–6**: `listeners` is the **Observer list**. Any View can register a `Runnable` to be called on Model change.
- Lines **17–22**: `getGrade()` is **business logic that lives inside the Model**, never in the View.
- Lines **25–34**: Mutators perform **validation** (defensive programming) and then call `fireChange()`.
- Lines **37–39**: This is the **classic Observer callback** — equivalent to `PropertyChangeListener` in JavaBeans.

## 3.4 Step 2 — The VIEW (Passive rendering only)

```java
// File: StudentView.java  — PASSIVE VIEW.
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class StudentView extends JFrame {

    // --- 1. UI widgets ---
    private final JLabel  lblName   = new JLabel("Name:");
    private final JLabel  lblRoll   = new JLabel("Roll No:");
    private final JLabel  lblMarks  = new JLabel("Marks:");
    private final JTextField tfName  = new JTextField(15);
    private final JTextField tfRoll  = new JTextField(15);
    private final JTextField tfMarks = new JTextField(15);
    private final JButton  btnSave  = new JButton("Save");
    private final JLabel   lblGrade = new JLabel("Grade: -");

    // --- 2. Constructor builds the GUI ---
    public StudentView() {
        setTitle("MVC Demo — Student");
        setLayout(new GridLayout(4, 2, 5, 5));
        add(lblName);  add(tfName);
        add(lblRoll);  add(tfRoll);
        add(lblMarks); add(tfMarks);
        add(btnSave);  add(lblGrade);
        setSize(350, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
    }

    // --- 3. Pure getters — Controller uses them to read input ---
    public String  getInputName()  { return tfName.getText(); }
    public int     getInputRoll()  { return Integer.parseInt(tfRoll.getText()); }
    public double  getInputMarks() { return Double.parseDouble(tfMarks.getText()); }

    // --- 4. Display helper — Controller pushes data here ---
    public void showStudent(String name, int roll, double marks, String grade) {
        tfName.setText(name);
        tfRoll.setText(String.valueOf(roll));
        tfMarks.setText(String.valueOf(marks));
        lblGrade.setText("Grade: " + grade);
    }

    // --- 5. Error dialog ---
    public void showError(String msg) {
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, msg, "Error", JOptionPane.ERROR_MESSAGE);
    }

    // --- 6. Listener registration — View hands events to Controller ---
    public void addSaveListener(java.awt.event.ActionListener l) {
        btnSave.addActionListener(l);
    }
}
```

**Step 2 explanation:**
- The View **never touches the Model directly** — it only exposes `getInput*()` methods.
- Line 27: `showStudent()` is the **rendering method** the Controller calls after Model update.
- Line 35: `addSaveListener()` is the **decoupling hook** — the View does not know which class will handle the click.

## 3.5 Step 3 — The CONTROLLER (Mediator)

```java
// File: StudentController.java  — THE MEDIATOR.
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;

public class StudentController {
    private final StudentModel model;
    private final StudentView  view;

    public StudentController(StudentModel model, StudentView view) {
        this.model = model;
        this.view  = view;

        // (a) View ➜ Controller : register event handler
        view.addSaveListener(this::onSaveClicked);

        // (b) Model ➜ View : subscribe to Model changes
        model.addChangeListener(this::refreshView);

        // (c) Initial render
        refreshView.run();
    }

    private void onSaveClicked(ActionEvent e) {
        try {
            model.setName(view.getInputName());
            model.setMarks(view.getInputMarks());
            // roll number kept constant in this demo
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException ex) {
            view.showError(ex.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private void refreshView() {
        view.showStudent(
            model.getName(),
            model.getRollNo(),
            model.getMarks(),
            model.getGrade()
        );
    }
}
```

**Step 3 explanation:**
- The Controller is the **only class that imports both Model and View**.
- `view.addSaveListener(this::onSaveClicked)` uses a **method reference** — equivalent to `ActionListener` registration.
- `model.addChangeListener(this::refreshView)` is the **Observer subscription** — guarantees the View updates automatically whenever the Model mutates.
- Validation errors are caught here and **forwarded to the View for display** — the Controller never throws UI dialogs itself.

## 3.6 Step 4 — The MAIN / Entry Point (Composition Root)

```java
// File: MVCMain.java
public class MVCMain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Construct Model with seed data.
        StudentModel model = new StudentModel("Ananya S", 47, 85.0);

        // 2. Construct View (does not know about Controller yet).
        StudentView view = new StudentView();

        // 3. Construct Controller — wires Model + View together.
        new StudentController(model, view);

        // 4. Show the View.
        view.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

**Step 4 explanation:**
- The composition of the three objects happens **exactly once, in one place** — the *composition root*.
- This makes unit-testing trivial: you can substitute a mock View to test the Controller.

## 3.7 Execution Flow Matrix (How the Pattern Self-Executes)

| Step | Trigger | Active Component | Action | Next State |
| :---: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Program start | `MVCMain` | Constructs M, V, C | `Controller` wires them |
| 2 | Initial render | `Controller.refreshView()` | Calls `view.showStudent(...)` | View displays seed data |
| 3 | User edits & clicks Save | `View` (event source) | Fires `ActionEvent` | Controller receives it |
| 4 | Controller validates | `Controller.onSaveClicked` | Reads inputs, calls `model.set*()` | Model mutates |
| 5 | Model validates business rule | `Model.setMarks(...)` | Throws on invalid range | Controller catches, View shows error |
| 6 | Model succeeds | `Model.fireChange()` | Iterates `listeners` | Controller's `refreshView` runs |
| 7 | Controller re-renders | `View.showStudent(...)` | Updates Swing components | User sees fresh Grade |

## 3.8 Analytical Matrix — Variation of MVC

| Variant | Year | Description | Used In |
| :--- | :---: | :--- | :--- |
| **Classic MVC** | 1979 | Model notifies multiple Views; View pulls from Model | Smalltalk |
| **MVP** (Model-View-Presenter) | 1990 | Presenter pushes data into a passive View | GWT, ASP.NET Web Forms |
| **MVVM** (Model-View-ViewModel) | 2005 | View binds declaratively to ViewModel | WPF, Angular, Vue, Flutter |
| **MVA** (Model-View-Adapter) | 1996 | Adapter mediates between Model & View | Cocoa (Apple) |

