# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 The Swing Class Hierarchy (Architectural Foundation)

The entire Swing library is anchored at `java.awt.Component` (inherited from AWT for compatibility) and branches down through `java.awt.Container` → `javax.swing.JComponent` → all the individual Swing controls.

The conceptual chain is:

`Object` → `Component` (AWT) → `Container` (AWT) → `JComponent` (Swing) → Specific Controls (`JButton`, `JLabel`, `JTextField`, etc.)

**Why this matters for OOP:** This is a textbook example of **multi-level inheritance** and **polymorphism** in action. A method like `setFont(Font f)` defined in `Component` is inherited and available on every Swing control — showcasing **code reuse** through inheritance.

## 2.2 The Event Delegation Model (EDM) — The Heart of Swing Interaction

Swing does **not** use the older Java 1.0 event-inheritance model. Instead, it uses the **Event Delegation Model**, which is built on three core participants:

1. **Event Source** — The GUI component where the event originates (e.g., a `JButton`).
2. **Event Object** — A subclass of `java.util.EventObject` that encapsulates the event details (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`).
3. **Event Listener** — An object that implements a listener interface (e.g., `ActionListener`, `MouseListener`) and is *registered* with the event source via a registration method (e.g., `button.addActionListener(listener)`).

**Operational Logic Flow:**

- The user interacts with the GUI (clicks a button, types a character).
- The **JVM** detects the interaction and creates an **Event Object** describing what happened.
- The event source checks its **listener list** and invokes the appropriate callback method on each registered listener.
- The listener's method executes the business logic.

> [!NOTE]
> **Single Listener, Multiple Sources:** The same listener object can be registered with multiple components, promoting **loose coupling** and adhering to the OOP principle of **dependency inversion**.

## 2.3 KTU Cheat Sheet — Swing Controls, Constructors, and Listeners

