> The following reference table is the **high-yield** material frequently tested in KTU 2024 Scheme ESE papers. Memorize the **Class Name → Constructor → Default Listener** mapping.

| Control Class | Common Constructor(s) | Purpose | Key Listener(s) |
|---|---|---|---|
| `JLabel` | `JLabel()`, `JLabel(String text)`, `JLabel(Icon icon)` | Displays uneditable text or icon | None (passive) |
| `JButton` | `JButton()`, `JButton(String text)`, `JButton(Icon icon)` | Clickable push button | `ActionListener` |
| `JTextField` | `JTextField()`, `JTextField(int cols)`, `JTextField(String text)` | Single-line text input | `ActionListener`, `KeyListener`, `FocusListener` |
| `JTextArea` | `JTextArea()`, `JTextArea(int rows, int cols)`, `JTextArea(String text)` | Multi-line text input/output | `KeyListener`, `FocusListener` |
| `JPasswordField` | `JPasswordField()`, `JPasswordField(int cols)` | Masked password input (extends `JTextField`) | `ActionListener` |
| `JCheckBox` | `JCheckBox()`, `JCheckBox(String text)`, `JCheckBox(String text, boolean selected)` | Toggle on/off checkbox | `ItemListener`, `ActionListener` |
| `JRadioButton` | `JRadioButton()`, `JRadioButton(String text)` | Mutually exclusive selection (group via `ButtonGroup`) | `ItemListener`, `ActionListener` |
| `JComboBox<E>` | `JComboBox()`, `JComboBox(E[] items)`, `JComboBox(Vector<E> items)` | Drop-down selection | `ItemListener`, `ActionListener` |
| `JList<E>` | `JList()`, `JList(E[] listData)`, `JList(Vector<E> listData)` | Scrollable list of selectable items | `ListSelectionListener` |
| `JTable` | `JTable()`, `JTable(int rows, int cols)`, `JTable(Object[][] data, Object[] cols)` | Tabular data display | `ListSelectionListener` |
| `JScrollPane` | `JScrollPane(Component view)` | Provides scroll bars to any component | N/A (wrapper) |
| `JSlider` | `JSlider(int min, int max, int value)` | Sliding numeric input | `ChangeListener` |
| `JProgressBar` | `JProgressBar(int min, int max)` | Visual progress indicator | `ChangeListener` |
| `JMenuBar / JMenu / JMenuItem` | `JMenu()`, `JMenu(String label)`, `JMenuItem(String label)` | Menu system (File, Edit, etc.) | `ActionListener` |
| `JPanel` | `JPanel()`, `JPanel(LayoutManager layout)` | Generic intermediate container | N/A (container) |
| `JTabbedPane` | `JTabbedPane()` | Tabbed interface | `ChangeListener` |
| `JSplitPane` | `JSplitPane(int orientation, Component c1, Component c2)` | Resizable split view | N/A |

## 2.4 Layout Managers — The Positioning Engine

Layout managers are objects that implement the `LayoutManager` interface and dictate how components are arranged within a container. The five **most exam-relevant** layout managers in the KTU 2024 syllabus are:

### 2.4.1 FlowLayout
- **Default layout** of `JPanel`.
- Places components left-to-right, top-to-bottom, in the order they were added.
- Respects each component's **preferred size**.
- Constructor: `FlowLayout()`, `FlowLayout(int align)`, `FlowLayout(int align, int hgap, int vgap)`.
- Alignments: `FlowLayout.LEFT`, `FlowLayout.CENTER` (default), `FlowLayout.RIGHT`.

### 2.4.2 BorderLayout
- **Default layout** of `JFrame`'s content pane.
- Divides the container into **5 regions**: `NORTH`, `SOUTH`, `EAST`, `WEST`, `CENTER`.
- The `CENTER` region gets all leftover space; the others size to their preferred dimensions.
- Each region can hold **only one component** — to add multiple, wrap them in a `JPanel`.

### 2.4.3 GridLayout
- Arranges components in a **uniform grid** of rows and columns.
- Constructor: `GridLayout(int rows, int cols)`, `GridLayout(int rows, int cols, int hgap, int vgap)`.
- All cells are **equal size**; components are stretched to fill their cell.

### 2.4.4 GridBagLayout
- The **most powerful and flexible** layout manager.
- Uses a `GridBagConstraints` object to specify per-component placement, fill behaviour, padding, and weight.
- Standard choice for complex, form-like GUIs.

### 2.4.5 BoxLayout
- Stacks components in a **single row** (`BoxLayout.X_AXIS`) or **single column** (`BoxLayout.Y_AXIS`).
- Constructor: `setLayout(new BoxLayout(panel, BoxLayout.Y_AXIS))`.
- Excellent for toolbars and vertical forms.

### 2.4.6 CardLayout
- Treats each component as a "card"; only one card is visible at a time.
- Useful for **wizard-style** interfaces and tabbed views.
- Methods: `first(container)`, `next(container)`, `previous(container)`, `show(container, name)`.

## 2.5 Adapter Classes — Bridging Interfaces and Concrete Classes

Many listener interfaces (e.g., `MouseListener`, `KeyListener`, `WindowListener`) declare **multiple methods**, but you often need to override only one. Implementing all methods is tedious. **Adapter classes** provide empty default implementations, so you override only what you need.

| Interface | Adapter Class | Key Method(s) Often Overridden |
|---|---|---|
| `MouseListener` | `MouseAdapter` | `mouseClicked(MouseEvent e)` |
| `KeyListener` | `KeyAdapter` | `keyTyped(KeyEvent e)` |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowAdapter` | `windowClosing(WindowEvent e)` |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusAdapter` | `focusGained(FocusEvent e)` |
| `ComponentListener` | `ComponentAdapter` | `componentResized(ComponentEvent e)` |

## 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

Swing is extensively used in:
- **Enterprise desktop tools**: IDEs (older NetBeans, IntelliJ's UI plugins), internal corporate dashboards, and POS systems.
- **Scientific and Engineering Software**: MATLAB's GUI builder, LabVIEW front panels, and SCADA systems use Swing-like widget toolkits.
- **Educational Software**: Interactive simulations, circuit designers, and learning platforms.
- **Banking and POS Terminals**: Java's write-once-run-anywhere nature made Swing the de-facto GUI for Java-based ATMs and POS in many countries.
- **OOP Pedagogy**: Swing is the canonical example used worldwide to teach **event-driven programming, inheritance, polymorphism, and the MVC pattern**.

> [!TIP]
> **Engineering Insight:** Swing's *pluggable look-and-feel* relies on the **Strategy design pattern** — the look-and-feel object is "strategized" into the UI, allowing runtime swapping of algorithms (L&F rules) without modifying the UI tree. This is a favourite OOP design pattern question in KTU exams.
