## 3.1 Walkthrough 1 — Building the Simplest Swing Application (Hello World with JButton)

This program demonstrates the **mandatory five-step structure** of every Swing application.

```java
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JButton;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;

public class HelloSwing {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // STEP 1: Create the top-level container (the main window)
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("My First Swing App");
        frame.setSize(400, 200);
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        // STEP 2: Set a layout manager (FlowLayout for simple left-to-right)
        frame.setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        // STEP 3: Create Swing controls (components)
        JButton clickButton = new JButton("Click Me!");
        JButton exitButton  = new JButton("Exit");

        // STEP 4: Register event listeners using the Event Delegation Model
        clickButton.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            @Override
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                System.out.println("Button clicked at: " + e.getWhen());
                System.out.println("Source component: " + e.getSource().getClass().getSimpleName());
            }
        });

        exitButton.addActionListener(e -> System.exit(0));   // Lambda (Java 8+)

        // STEP 5: Add components to the frame and make it visible
        frame.add(clickButton);
        frame.add(exitButton);
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

**Explanatory Commentary (board-style):**
- *Step 1* instantiates a `JFrame` — the *only* top-level container you can directly show.
- `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` ensures the JVM terminates when the window is closed. Without this, the window closes but the program continues running in the background.
- *Step 2* assigns a layout manager. Omitting this defaults to `BorderLayout` for `JFrame` content pane.
- *Step 3* creates the controls. The `JButton` constructor accepting a `String` sets the displayed label.
- *Step 4* implements the **Event Delegation Model** — the button is the *source*, `ActionEvent` is the *event object*, and the anonymous inner class is the *listener*. The `actionPerformed` method is the **callback**.
- *Step 5* adds components and reveals the window. `setVisible(true)` must be called **after** all components are added, otherwise the layout may not render correctly.

## 3.2 Walkthrough 2 — Form with JLabel, JTextField, JPasswordField, and JButton

A classic login form demonstrating multiple controls and `GridLayout`.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class LoginForm extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    JLabel     userLabel, passLabel, messageLabel;
    JTextField userField;
    JPasswordField passField;
    JButton    loginButton, resetButton;

    public LoginForm() {
        setTitle("Login Form");
        setSize(350, 200);
        setLayout(new GridLayout(4, 2, 10, 10));   // 4 rows, 2 cols, 10px gaps

        // Constructing controls
        userLabel    = new JLabel("Username:");
        userField    = new JTextField();
        passLabel    = new JLabel("Password:");
        passField    = new JPasswordField();
        messageLabel = new JLabel(" ");
        loginButton  = new JButton("Login");
        resetButton  = new JButton("Reset");

        // Registering listeners — 'this' because the frame implements ActionListener
        loginButton.addActionListener(this);
        resetButton.addActionListener(this);

        // Adding components in row-major order (GridLayout)
        add(userLabel);  add(userField);
        add(passLabel);  add(passField);
        add(loginButton); add(resetButton);
        add(messageLabel); add(new JLabel());   // blank filler cell

        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == loginButton) {
            String user = userField.getText();
            String pass = new String(passField.getPassword());
            if (user.equals("admin") && pass.equals("1234"))
                messageLabel.setText("Login successful!");
            else
                messageLabel.setText("Invalid credentials.");
        } else if (e.getSource() == resetButton) {
            userField.setText("");
            passField.setText("");
            messageLabel.setText(" ");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new LoginForm();
    }
}
```

**Explanatory Notes:**
- The class **implements `ActionListener`**, so a single instance (`this`) serves as the listener for both buttons — this is the **recommended best practice** to avoid anonymous-class clutter.
- `e.getSource()` returns the *actual button object* that fired the event, allowing the listener to branch its logic.
- `GridLayout(4, 2, 10, 10)` creates 4 rows × 2 columns with 10px horizontal and vertical gaps.
- `new String(passField.getPassword())` is the secure way to read a password — `getPassword()` returns a `char[]`, not a `String`, so it can be cleared from memory.

## 3.3 Walkthrough 3 — JCheckBox, JRadioButton, and ButtonGroup

Demonstrating toggle controls and mutually exclusive selection.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class SelectionDemo extends JFrame implements ItemListener {

    JCheckBox  javaCheck, pythonCheck;
    JRadioButton maleRadio, femaleRadio, otherRadio;
    JLabel      outputLabel;

    public SelectionDemo() {
        setTitle("Selection Controls");
        setSize(400, 250);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.LEFT));

        javaCheck   = new JCheckBox("Java");
        pythonCheck = new JCheckBox("Python");
        javaCheck.addItemListener(this);
        pythonCheck.addItemListener(this);

        maleRadio   = new JRadioButton("Male");
        femaleRadio = new JRadioButton("Female");
        otherRadio  = new JRadioButton("Other");
        // ButtonGroup enforces mutual exclusivity among radio buttons
        ButtonGroup genderGroup = new ButtonGroup();
        genderGroup.add(maleRadio);
        genderGroup.add(femaleRadio);
        genderGroup.add(otherRadio);
        maleRadio.addItemListener(this);
        femaleRadio.addItemListener(this);
        otherRadio.addItemListener(this);

        outputLabel = new JLabel("Select your preferences.");

        add(new JLabel("Languages:"));
        add(javaCheck);
        add(pythonCheck);
        add(new JLabel("Gender:"));
        add(maleRadio);
        add(femaleRadio);
        add(otherRadio);
        add(outputLabel);

        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e) {
        String langs  = (javaCheck.isSelected() ? "Java " : "")
                      + (pythonCheck.isSelected() ? "Python " : "");
        String gender = maleRadio.isSelected()   ? "Male"
                      : femaleRadio.isSelected() ? "Female"
                      : otherRadio.isSelected()  ? "Other" : "None";
        outputLabel.setText("Languages: " + langs.trim() + " | Gender: " + gender);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new SelectionDemo();
    }
}
```

**Critical Concept — ButtonGroup vs Container:**
- The **`ButtonGroup`** is *not* a visible container; it is a logical grouping that enforces *single-selection* among its member radio buttons.
- The radio buttons are still **physically added to the frame** (or panel), not to the `ButtonGroup`.
- This is a common board exam pitfall — students often confuse `ButtonGroup` with `JPanel`.

## 3.4 Walkthrough 4 — JComboBox and JList

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class DropdownListDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener, ListSelectionListener {

    JLabel      chooseLabel, outputLabel;
    JComboBox<String> countryCombo;
    JList<String>     cityList;
    String[] countries = {"India", "USA", "UK", "Japan"};
    String[][] cities  = {
        {"Delhi", "Mumbai", "Chennai"},
        {"New York", "Chicago", "Los Angeles"},
        {"London", "Manchester", "Liverpool"},
        {"Tokyo", "Osaka", "Kyoto"}
    };

    public DropdownListDemo() {
        setTitle("ComboBox & List Demo");
        setSize(400, 250);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.LEFT));

        chooseLabel = new JLabel("Choose a country: ");
        countryCombo = new JComboBox<>(countries);
        countryCombo.addActionListener(this);

        cityList = new JList<>(cities[0]);
        cityList.setVisibleRowCount(3);
        cityList.setSelectionMode(ListSelectionModel.SINGLE_SELECTION);
        cityList.addListSelectionListener(this);

        outputLabel = new JLabel("Output will appear here.");

        add(chooseLabel);
        add(countryCombo);
        add(new JScrollPane(cityList));
        add(outputLabel);

        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        int idx = countryCombo.getSelectedIndex();
        cityList.setListData(cities[idx]);
        outputLabel.setText("Selected country: " + countries[idx]);
    }

    @Override
    public void valueChanged(ListSelectionEvent e) {
        if (!e.getValueIsAdjusting()) {
