        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new DropdownListDemo();
    }
}
```

**Important Pattern — `e.getValueIsAdjusting()`:** When a user drags the mouse across list items, multiple `ListSelectionEvent`s fire. Checking `getValueIsAdjusting()` ensures the code runs only **once** when the selection stabilizes — a common board exam interview point.

## 3.5 Walkthrough 5 — Menu System (JMenuBar, JMenu, JMenuItem)

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class MenuDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    JMenuBar menuBar;
    JMenu fileMenu, editMenu, helpMenu;
    JMenuItem newItem, openItem, saveItem, exitItem, aboutItem;
    JTextArea textArea;

    public MenuDemo() {
        setTitle("Menu Demo");
        setSize(500, 400);
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());

        textArea = new JTextArea();
        add(new JScrollPane(textArea), BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // STEP 1: Create the menu bar
        menuBar = new JMenuBar();

        // STEP 2: Create top-level menus
        fileMenu = new JMenu("File");
        editMenu = new JMenu("Edit");
        helpMenu = new JMenu("Help");

        // STEP 3: Create menu items
        newItem   = new JMenuItem("New");
        openItem  = new JMenuItem("Open");
        saveItem  = new JMenuItem("Save");
        exitItem  = new JMenuItem("Exit");
        aboutItem = new JMenuItem("About");

        newItem.addActionListener(this);
        openItem.addActionListener(this);
        saveItem.addActionListener(this);
        exitItem.addActionListener(this);
        aboutItem.addActionListener(this);

        // STEP 4: Add items to menus
        fileMenu.add(newItem);
        fileMenu.add(openItem);
        fileMenu.add(saveItem);
        fileMenu.addSeparator();   // visual divider
        fileMenu.add(exitItem);

        helpMenu.add(aboutItem);

        // STEP 5: Add menus to the menu bar, and menu bar to the frame
        menuBar.add(fileMenu);
        menuBar.add(editMenu);
        menuBar.add(helpMenu);
        setJMenuBar(menuBar);

        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        Object src = e.getSource();
        if (src == newItem)        textArea.setText("");
        else if (src == openItem)  JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Open dialog (stub).");
        else if (src == saveItem)  JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Save dialog (stub).");
        else if (src == exitItem)  System.exit(0);
        else if (src == aboutItem) JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Menu Demo v1.0");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new MenuDemo();
    }
}
```

**Key Method — `setJMenuBar()`:** Use this on the `JFrame` (not `add()`), as it specifically positions the menu bar at the OS-native location of the window.

