## 4.2 Event Delegation Model — Sequence Flow

This diagram shows the **end-to-end flow** of a button click in the Event Delegation Model.

```mermaid
graph TD
    userA[User Clicks JButton]
    jvmStep[JVM Creates ActionEvent]
    srcStep[Event Source Button looks up registered listeners]
    invStep[Invokes actionPerformed on each Listener]
    bizStep[Listener executes business logic]
    upStep[UI updates e.g. setText on JLabel]

    userA --> jvmStep
    jvmStep --> srcStep
    srcStep --> invStep
    invStep --> bizStep
    bizStep --> upStep
```

**Interpretation:** Notice how the *event source* (button) does **not** contain business logic. It only delegates the event to a registered listener. This **decouples** the UI from the logic — a cornerstone of the MVC pattern and the **Dependency Inversion Principle** of SOLID OOP design.

## 4.3 Container-Component Architectural Block

A block-level functional architecture of how a typical Swing window is constructed.

```mermaid
graph TD
    frmBlock[JFrame Top Level Container]
    cpBlock[Content Pane Default BorderLayout]
    nbBlock[North JPanel with JLabel title]
    ctBlock[Center JPanel with FlowLayout]
    sbBlock[South JPanel with GridLayout 1 2]
    btnA[JButton Submit]
    btnB[JButton Cancel]
    mbarBlock[JMenuBar attached via setJMenuBar]
    mA[JMenu File]
    mB[JMenu Edit]

    frmBlock --> cpBlock
    frmBlock --> mbarBlock
    cpBlock --> nbBlock
    cpBlock --> ctBlock
    cpBlock --> sbBlock
    sbBlock --> btnA
    sbBlock --> btnB
    mbarBlock --> mA
    mbarBlock --> mB
```

**Architectural Insight:** Best-practice Swing GUIs nest **`JPanel`s** inside the `JFrame`'s `BorderLayout` regions. Each panel uses its own layout manager — this composition pattern is called the **"Nested Layout Pattern"** and is the standard way to build non-trivial GUIs.

## 4.4 Layout Manager Decision Tree

```mermaid
graph TD
    qStart{Need a GUI layout?}
    q1{Linear or grid arrangement?}
    q2{Single row or column?}
