### Question 1
**[KTU University Exam — May 2024 Model Paper]**
Differentiate between AWT and Swing. List any three distinguishing features.

**Model Answer:**

| Feature | AWT | Swing |
|---|---|---|
| Package | `java.awt` | `javax.swing` |
| Component type | Heavyweight (relies on OS peers) | Mostly lightweight (rendered by Java) |
| Look-and-feel | OS-dependent | Pluggable (PLAF) |
| Class prefix | `Button`, `TextField` | `JButton`, `JTextField` |
| MVC support | Limited | Full |
| Performance | Faster on some platforms | Slightly slower due to Java rendering |

AWT components are part of the **original Java 1.0** toolkit and depend on the underlying operating system for rendering, making them platform-dependent. Swing, introduced in **Java 1.2** (part of JFC), renders components in pure Java, providing true platform independence and a richer, more flexible set of features.

---

### Question 2
**[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
What is the Event Delegation Model in Java? Name its three participants.

**Model Answer:**

The **Event Delegation Model (EDM)** is Swing's mechanism for handling user interactions. Instead of a container processing its own events (as in the older Java 1.0 model), the event is *delegated* to a registered listener object.

The three participants are:
1. **Event Source** — The GUI component (e.g., `JButton`) on which the event occurs. It maintains a list of registered listeners.
2. **Event Object** — A subclass of `java.util.EventObject` (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`) that carries information about the event.
3. **Event Listener** — An object implementing a listener interface (e.g., `ActionListener`) whose callback method is invoked when the event fires.

