### Question A (Choice 1) — 14 Marks
**[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024, Adapted]**

**(a)** Explain any **five layout managers** in Java Swing with their constructors and behaviour. (7 marks)

**(b)** Write a complete Java Swing program that creates a form with a `JLabel`, `JTextField`, `JButton`, and `JTextArea`. When the user types a name in the text field and clicks the button, the textarea should display *"Hello, &lt;name&gt;!"*. (7 marks)

---

#### Model Solution for (a) — Five Layout Managers

1. **`FlowLayout`** — Arranges components left-to-right in rows. When a row is full, it wraps to the next row. Default for `JPanel`.
   Constructors: `FlowLayout()`, `FlowLayout(int align)`, `FlowLayout(int align, int hgap, int vgap)`.

2. **`BorderLayout`** — Divides the container into five regions: `NORTH`, `SOUTH`, `EAST`, `WEST`, `CENTER`. Each region holds exactly one component; the `CENTER` consumes all leftover space. Default for `JFrame`'s content pane.

3. **`GridLayout`** — Arranges components in a rectangular grid of equally-sized cells. Components are stretched to fill their cell.
   Constructor: `GridLayout(int rows, int cols, int hgap, int vgap)`.

4. **`GridBagLayout`** — The most flexible manager. Each component is placed according to a `GridBagConstraints` object specifying grid position, fill, weight, insets, and padding. Allows non-uniform cell sizes and overlapping — ideal for complex forms.

5. **`CardLayout`** — Treats each component as a "card"; only one card is visible at a time. Used for wizard-style step-by-step UIs.
   Key methods: `first(parent)`, `next(parent)`, `previous(parent)`, `show(parent, name)`.

6. **`BoxLayout`** *(bonus)* — Stacks components in a single row (`X_AXIS`) or column (`Y_AXIS`). Allows alignment via glue and rigid areas.

---

#### Model Solution for (b) — Greeting Form

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class GreetingForm extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    JLabel     nameLabel;
    JTextField nameField;
    JButton    greetButton;
    JTextArea  outputArea;

    public GreetingForm() {
        setTitle("Greeting Form");
        setSize(400, 300);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new BorderLayout(10, 10));

        // North region: input panel
        JPanel inputPanel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());
        nameLabel  = new JLabel("Enter your name: ");
        nameField  = new JTextField(15);
        greetButton = new JButton("Greet");
        greetButton.addActionListener(this);
        inputPanel.add(nameLabel);
        inputPanel.add(nameField);
        inputPanel.add(greetButton);
        add(inputPanel, BorderLayout.NORTH);

        // Center region: output
        outputArea = new JTextArea();
        outputArea.setEditable(false);
        add(new JScrollPane(outputArea), BorderLayout.CENTER);

        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = nameField.getText().trim();
        if (name.isEmpty()) {
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Please enter a name.");
        } else {
            outputArea.append("Hello, " + name + "!\n");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new GreetingForm();
    }
}
```

**Explanation of Key Lines (board-style commentary):**
- `setLayout(new BorderLayout(10, 10))` sets a 10-pixel gap between regions.
- The input components are nested in a `JPanel` using `FlowLayout` — this is the **nested-layout pattern**.
- `outputArea.setEditable(false)` prevents the user from modifying the displayed greetings.
- `JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, ...)` displays a modal error dialog when the name is empty, demonstrating **input validation**.
- `outputArea.append(...)` adds a new line of greeting without clearing the previous ones.

