## SECTION 1 — Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Event Handling** in Java Swings is the mechanism by which a Graphical User Interface (GUI) component (the *event source*) communicates with the application code (the *event listener / handler*) to respond to user interactions such as clicks, key presses, mouse movements, window resizing, and focus changes. KTU 2024 Scheme defines event handling under the **Delegation Event Model (DEM)**, where the responsibility of handling an event generated by a component is *delegated* to a registered object (the listener), rather than the component handling the event itself.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight (Module 4):** Students must understand the **Delegation Event Model**, the hierarchy of `java.awt.event` and `javax.swing.event` packages, the role of **Event Sources**, **Event Objects**, and **Event Listeners**, and must be able to write programs using **ActionListener**, **MouseListener**, **KeyListener**, **WindowListener**, and their corresponding **Adapter classes**, often using **inner / anonymous classes**.

### 1.2 Key Terminology (KTU Board Vocabulary)

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Event** | An object that describes a state change in a GUI component (e.g., a button was clicked). |
| **Event Source** | The GUI component that generates the event (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`). |
| **Event Listener / Handler** | An object that implements a listener interface and receives the event. |
| **Event Object** | A subclass of `java.util.EventObject` carrying event information. |
| **Delegation Event Model** | The architecture where source delegates event processing to registered listeners. |

### 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — The Doorbell System

Imagine a **doorbell** in your house. When a visitor presses the doorbell button (**Event Source**), an electrical signal travels through the wiring (**Event Dispatching Thread**), and a buzzer inside the kitchen rings (**Event Listener / Handler**). The doorbell *itself* does not know how to make the sound; it **delegates** the task. Similarly, a `JButton` in Java does not know what to do when clicked; it delegates the task to a `Listener` object that we register. If nobody is registered, the click is silently ignored — exactly like a doorbell with no buzzer wired to it.

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-world KTU pattern:** Almost every KTU 2024 OOP exam question features a `JButton` triggering an `ActionListener` that updates a `JLabel` or performs a calculation. Mastering this single pattern covers roughly 60% of Part A marks in this module.

