## SECTION 2 — Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Delegation Event Model — Step-by-Step Logic

The Delegation Event Model operates on **four** tightly-coupled logical steps. KTU examiners love to ask: *"Explain the Delegation Event Model with a diagram."* Memorize the following flow:

1. **User Interaction Occurs** — The user performs an action (click, key press, mouse move) on a GUI component.
2. **Event Object is Created** — The AWT/Swing event-dispatching thread constructs an `EventObject` subclass (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`) populated with source, ID, coordinates, etc.
3. **Event is Dispatched** — The component iterates through its internal list of registered listeners and invokes the appropriate callback method (e.g., `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`).
4. **Listener Executes Logic** — The listener's overridden method runs the application code we wrote, then control returns to the GUI thread.

### 2.2 Why "Delegation"? — The Core Engineering Rationale

In older Java AWT (pre-1.1), components inherited huge `handleEvent()` methods. This violated **OOP encapsulation** and produced the infamous "spaghetti code." The Delegation Model fixes this by separating *event generation* (the component) from *event consumption* (the listener), allowing:
- **Multiple listeners** on a single source (e.g., two listeners on one button).
- **Single listener** to handle multiple sources (e.g., one handler for 10 buttons).
- **Loose coupling** between UI and business logic.

### 2.3 The Event Handling API — KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The following table is the **single most important reference** for KTU 2024 ESE preparation on this topic. Memorize the mapping between **Event Class** and its **Listener Interface**.

| Event Class (Package) | Listener Interface | Key Method(s) | Adapter Class |
|---|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` (`awt.event`) | `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent)` | — |
| `MouseEvent` (`awt.event`) | `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited` | `MouseAdapter` |
| `MouseEvent` (`awt.event`) | `MouseMotionListener` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved` | `MouseMotionAdapter` |
| `KeyEvent` (`awt.event`) | `KeyListener` | `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased` | `KeyAdapter` |
| `WindowEvent` (`awt.event`) | `WindowListener` | 7 methods incl. `windowClosing`, `windowOpened` | `WindowAdapter` |
| `FocusEvent` (`awt.event`) | `FocusListener` | `focusGained`, `focusLost` | `FocusAdapter` |
| `ItemEvent` (`awt.event`) | `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent)` | — |
| `ChangeEvent` (`swing.event`) | `ChangeListener` | `stateChanged(ChangeEvent)` | — |
| `ListSelectionEvent` (`swing.event`) | `ListSelectionListener` | `valueChanged(ListSelectionEvent)` | — |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** `ActionEvent` and `ItemEvent` have **no Adapter class** because each has only a single callback method. You *must* implement the interface directly.

### 2.4 Engineering Utility

In real-world Swing applications, event handling is the **bridge between the UI layer and the business logic layer**. Banking apps, IDEs (NetBeans, IntelliJ use Swing plugins), ERP systems, and KTU's own lab evaluation software all rely on the Delegation Event Model. The `Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)` ensures **thread safety** in GUI updates.

