Because *Event Handling* is a procedural/OOP topic rather than a mathematical one, the "derivations" here take the form of **exhaustive code walkthroughs** following KTU board-style evaluation. Every line is explained.

### 3.1 Derivation-I: The Canonical "Button-Click-Updates-Label" Pattern

This is the **single most important program** for KTU Module 4. The KTU board typically awards **14 marks** for this pattern with minor variations.

**Problem Statement (KTU-Style):** *Write a Java Swing program to create a frame containing a JTextField, a JButton labeled "Greet", and a JLabel. When the button is clicked, the text from the JTextField should appear on the JLabel prefixed with "Hello, ".*

**Step 1 — Import the required packages.**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

*Logic:* `javax.swing.*` gives access to all Swing components (`JFrame`, `JButton`, etc.). `java.awt.*` provides `FlowLayout` and `BorderLayout`. `java.awt.event.*` provides the `ActionListener` and `ActionEvent` classes needed for click handling.

**Step 2 — Create the public class extending `JFrame` and implementing `ActionListener`.**

```java
public class GreetApp extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JLabel label;
    JTextField textField;
    JButton button;
```

*Logic:* Implementing `ActionListener` here means *this* frame object itself will be the handler. This is a common KTU pattern (the outer class as listener).

**Step 3 — Write the constructor to assemble the GUI.**

```java
    GreetApp() {
        setTitle("KTU Greet App");
        setSize(400, 150);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        textField = new JTextField(15);
        button = new JButton("Greet");
        label = new JLabel("Type your name and click Greet.");

        add(textField);
        add(button);
        add(label);

        button.addActionListener(this);   // <-- Registration step

        setVisible(true);
    }
```

*Logic:* The critical line is `button.addActionListener(this)`. This **registers** the current object as the listener for the button's action events. The method `addActionListener` accepts any object implementing the `ActionListener` interface.

**Step 4 — Override the `actionPerformed` method (the actual handler).**

```java
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = textField.getText();
        label.setText("Hello, " + name + "!");
    }
```

*Logic:* When the button is clicked, the EDT automatically calls this method. We read text from the field using `getText()` and update the label using `setText()`.

**Step 5 — Provide the `main` method.**

```java
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new GreetApp();
    }
}
```

*Logic:* We instantiate the frame. Swing components should be created on the **Event Dispatch Thread** in production code (`SwingUtilities.invokeLater`), but for KTU exams, direct instantiation from `main` is accepted.

**Complete Program (Ready for KTU Answer Sheet):**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class GreetApp extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JLabel label;
    JTextField textField;
    JButton button;

    GreetApp() {
        setTitle("KTU Greet App");
        setSize(400, 150);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        textField = new JTextField(15);
        button   = new JButton("Greet");
        label    = new JLabel("Type your name and click Greet.");

        add(textField);
        add(button);
        add(label);

        button.addActionListener(this);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = textField.getText();
        label.setText("Hello, " + name + "!");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new GreetApp();
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Derivation-II: Adapter Class Pattern for Window Events

**Problem Statement:** *Write a program that closes the application only when the user clicks the window's close button (handle `windowClosing`). Use an **adapter class** instead of implementing all 7 methods of `WindowListener`.*

**Why an Adapter?** `WindowListener` has 7 abstract methods. Implementing the interface forces you to write empty bodies for all 7. The **`WindowAdapter`** class provides empty default implementations so you override *only* what you need.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class AdapterDemo extends JFrame {
    AdapterDemo() {
        setTitle("Adapter Demo");
        setSize(300, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE);

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new AdapterDemo();
    }
}
```

*Logic Line-by-Line:*
- `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE)` — disables the default close action so we can handle it manually.
- `addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() { ... })` — we pass an **anonymous inner class** that *extends* `WindowAdapter` and overrides only `windowClosing`.
- `System.exit(0)` — terminates the JVM cleanly.

### 3.3 Derivation-III: Identifying the Source of an Event

When one listener handles **multiple** buttons, we use `e.getSource()` to identify which button fired.

```java
public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
    if (e.getSource() == button1) {
        label.setText("Button 1 clicked");
    } else if (e.getSource() == button2) {
        label.setText("Button 2 clicked");
    }
}
```

*Logic:* `ActionEvent` inherits `getSource()` from `EventObject`. It returns the `Object` reference of the component that generated the event.

