**Concept of Adapter Classes (3 marks):**
Adapter classes provide empty default implementations of listener interfaces that declare **more than one abstract method**. They exist purely for convenience: by extending an adapter, the programmer overrides only the methods of interest, avoiding boilerplate empty method bodies. Adapters are defined for listener interfaces that have multiple methods (e.g., `WindowAdapter`, `KeyAdapter`, `MouseAdapter`). Adapters do **not** exist for single-method interfaces like `ActionListener`.

