## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Mathematical Derivation of Position Pointer

To insert a node at position $k$ in a singly linked list, we must identify the node at position $k-1$. Let the linked list be represented as a sequence:

$$L = \{n_1, n_2, n_3, \ldots, n_n\}$$

Where $n_i$ denotes the $i^{th}$ node, and each $n_i$ has a pointer $p_i = \text{address}(n_{i+1})$, with $p_n = \text{NULL}$.

**Derivation of the traversal condition:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Let } & \text{temp} = \text{head} \\
\text{Initialize counter: } & i = 1 \\
\text{Loop while: } & i < k - 1 \\
\text{Advance: } & \text{temp} = \text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next} \\
& i = i + 1 \\
\text{Terminate when: } & i = k - 1
\end{aligned}
$$

At loop termination, `temp` points to $n_{k-1}$, the node *before* the insertion point.

**Pointer re-routing equations (Singly Linked List):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{newNode} \rightarrow \text{next} &= \text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next} \\
\text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next} &= \text{newNode}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Pointer re-routing equations (Doubly Linked List):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{newNode} \rightarrow \text{next} &= \text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next} \\
\text{newNode} \rightarrow \text{prev} &= \text{temp} \\
(\text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next}) \rightarrow \text{prev} &= \text{newNode} \\
\text{temp} \rightarrow \text{next} &= \text{newNode}
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Insertion in Different Linked List Variants

| Parameter | Singly Linked List | Doubly Linked List | Circular Linked List |
|-----------|-------------------|--------------------|--------------------|
| Pointers per node | 1 (`next`) | 2 (`prev`, `next`) | 1 (`next`) |
| Insert at begin | $O(1)$, 1 step | $O(1)$, 4 steps | $O(1)$, 2 steps |
| Insert at end | $O(n)$ without tail | $O(1)$ with tail | $O(1)$ with tail |
| Insert at middle | $O(k)$ | $O(k)$ | $O(k)$ |
| Last node next | `NULL` | `NULL` | Points to **head** |
| Special check needed | No | No | **Yes** — circular condition |

### 3.3 Worked Example: Insertion at Position 3

**Initial List:** `10 → 20 → 30 → 40 → NULL`

**Task:** Insert `25` at position 3.

**Step-by-step evaluation:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial list: } & L = \{10, 20, 30, 40\} \\
\text{Position to insert: } & k = 3 \\
\text{New element: } & x = 25 \\
\text{After insertion: } & L' = \{10, 20, 25, 30, 40\}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Pointer re-routing in detail:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1: Traverse to } n_{k-1} &= n_2 = 20 \\
\text{Step 2: newNode} \rightarrow \text{next} &= n_2 \rightarrow \text{next} = 30 \\
\text{Step 3: } n_2 \rightarrow \text{next} &= \text{newNode} \\
\text{Final: } & 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 25 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow \text{NULL}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> Notice that **no existing node's data was modified** — only pointer references were updated. This is the defining characteristic of linked list insertion.

