**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**

What is the time complexity of inserting a node at the beginning of a singly linked list? Justify.

**Model Answer:**

The time complexity is $O(1)$ — constant time.

**Justification:** Only **two pointer operations** are required: assign `newNode->next = head` and `head = newNode`. No traversal is needed regardless of list size $n$. Therefore, the operation does not scale with $n$, yielding $T(n) = O(1)$.

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Module Internal Choice)

---

#### **Question A (14 Marks)** — *[KTU Model Question Paper Style]*

**(a)** Explain the algorithm to insert a node at the **end** of a singly linked list with a neat diagram. State its time complexity. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a C++ program using **classes** to implement insertion of a node at the **beginning**, **end**, and at a **given position** in a singly linked list. **(7 marks)**

---

**Model Solution for (a):**

**Algorithm: `insertAtEnd(data)`**

```
Step 1: newNode = allocate memory
Step 2: newNode->data = data
Step 3: newNode->next = NULL
Step 4: IF head == NULL THEN
            head = newNode
            RETURN
Step 5: temp = head
Step 6: WHILE temp->next != NULL
            temp = temp->next
Step 7: temp->next = newNode
Step 8: RETURN
```

**Diagram:**

```
Before:  HEAD → [10|•] → [20|•] → [30|NULL]

After:   HEAD → [10|•] → [20|•] → [30|•] → [40|NULL]
                                        ↑ newNode inserted
```

**Time Complexity Analysis:**

$$
T(n) = \begin{cases} O(1) & \text{if list is empty (best case)} \\ O(n) & \text{otherwise (worst case, traverse all nodes)} \end{cases}
$$

---

**Model Solution for (b) — C++ Implementation:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Node {
public:
    int data;
    Node* next;
    Node(int val) : data(val), next(NULL) {}
};

class LinkedList {
private:
    Node* head;
public:
    LinkedList() : head(NULL) {}

    // Insert at beginning - O(1)
    void insertAtBegin(int val) {
        Node* newNode = new Node(val);
        newNode->next = head;
        head = newNode;
        cout << val << " inserted at beginning." << endl;
    }

    // Insert at end - O(n)
    void insertAtEnd(int val) {
        Node* newNode = new Node(val);
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;
            return;
        }
        Node* temp = head;
        while (temp->next != NULL) {
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        temp->next = newNode;
        cout << val << " inserted at end." << endl;
    }

    // Insert at position - O(k)
    void insertAtPosition(int val, int pos) {
        if (pos < 1) {
            cout << "Invalid position!" << endl;
            return;
        }
        if (pos == 1) {
            insertAtBegin(val);
            return;
        }
        Node* newNode = new Node(val);
        Node* temp = head;
        for (int i = 1; i < pos - 1 && temp != NULL; i++) {
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        if (temp == NULL) {
            cout << "Position out of range!" << endl;
            return;
        }
        newNode->next = temp->next;
        temp->next = newNode;
        cout << val << " inserted at position " << pos << endl;
    }

    void display() {
        Node* temp = head;
        while (temp != NULL) {
            cout << temp->data << " -> ";
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        cout << "NULL" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    LinkedList list;
    list.insertAtEnd(10);
    list.insertAtEnd(20);
    list.insertAtEnd(30);
    list.insertAtBegin(5);
    list.insertAtPosition(15, 3);
    list.display();
    return 0;
}
```

---

#### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *Alternative Choice*

**(a)** With a suitable diagram, explain the procedure to insert a node at a **given position in a doubly linked list**. Compare its complexity with singly linked list insertion. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a C++ class definition for a **circular singly linked list** and implement the `insertAtEnd` operation. Why does circular insertion require an additional check compared to linear lists? **(7 marks)**

---

**Model Solution for (a):**

**Procedure for Insertion at Position $k$ in Doubly Linked List:**

```
Step 1: newNode = allocate memory
Step 2: newNode->data = data
Step 3: IF k == 1 THEN
            newNode->next = head
            newNode->prev = NULL
            IF head != NULL THEN head->prev = newNode
            head = newNode
            RETURN
Step 4: temp = head
Step 5: FOR i = 1 to k-1
            temp = temp->next
Step 6: newNode->next = temp->next
Step 7: newNode->prev = temp
Step 8: IF temp->next != NULL THEN
            temp->next->prev = newNode
Step 9: temp->next = newNode
```

**Diagram:**

```
     NULL ← [10] ⇄ [20] ⇄ [40] → NULL
                ↑     ↑     ↑
              prev  newNode  prev
                    (data=30)
```

**Complexity Comparison:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{\text{singly}}(k) &= O(k) \\
T_{\text{doubly}}(k) &= O(k) \text{ (same time, but bidirectional traversal possible)}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Trade-off:** Doubly linked list uses **2 pointers per node** (extra memory $O(n)$), but enables **deletion in $O(1)$** when node reference is given.

---

**Model Solution for (b) — Circular Linked List:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class CNode {
public:
    int data;
    CNode* next;
    CNode(int val) : data(val), next(NULL) {}
};

class CircularLinkedList {
private:
    CNode* head;
public:
    CircularLinkedList() : head(NULL) {}

    void insertAtEnd(int val) {
        CNode* newNode = new CNode(val);
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;
            newNode->next = head;   // Circular link
            return;
        }
        CNode* temp = head;
        // Special check: stop when next points back to head
        while (temp->next != head) {
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        temp->next = newNode;
        newNode->next = head;       // Maintain circular property
    }

    void display() {
        if (head == NULL) return;
        CNode* temp = head;
        do {
            cout << temp->data << " -> ";
            temp = temp->next;
        } while (temp != head);
        cout << "(back to head)" << endl;
    }
};
```

**Why additional check is needed:**

> [!WARNING]
> In a linear list, the loop termination condition is `temp->next == NULL`. In a circular list, **no node ever points to NULL** — the last node's `next` points back to `head`. Therefore, the loop must use `temp->next != head` as the termination condition, otherwise it results in **infinite loop** — a common KTU exam pitfall.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting to update `head`** after insertion at position 1 — leads to lost node.
> 2. **Memory leak:** Not using `delete` for removed/old nodes (relevant in deletion context).
> 3. **Infinite loop in circular lists** due to wrong termination condition.
> 4. **Not checking for `NULL` head** before traversal — causes segmentation fault.
> 5. **Wrong pointer order:** In doubly linked list, setting `temp->next = newNode` before `newNode->prev = temp` breaks the chain.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Insertion** is a **CO2/CO4** level OOP topic in KTU 2024 Scheme.
- Three canonical positions: **Beginning**, **End**, **Given Position**.
- Time complexity at **beginning** = $O(1)$ always (no traversal).
- Time complexity at **end** = $O(n)$ without tail pointer, $O(1)$ with tail pointer.
- **Singly linked list** uses one pointer (`next`); **Doubly** uses two (`prev`, `next`); **Circular** has last node pointing to head.
- In **circular lists**, loop termination uses `temp->next != head` — never `NULL`.
- Insertion requires **dynamic memory allocation** using `new` in C++.
- **Encapsulation:** Insert operations are public member functions; node structure is private.
- **Real-world applications:** OS process queues, music playlists, undo-redo editors, memory allocators.
- **Key exam formula:** $T(n) = O(k)$ for inserting at position $k$ in a list of size $n$.

> **Final Tip:** Always draw the linked list diagram before writing the algorithm — KTU examiners award **2–3 marks** for correct diagrams in insertion questions.
